1. Method Hiding in Java

Question / IQ:

What is Method Hiding in Java?
Can we override a static method?
Can we override the main method?

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Definition:

Method Hiding occurs when a static method in a subclass has the same name and signature as a static method in the superclass.
Important: Static methods belong to class, not objects.
Hence: Static methods cannot be overridden. They can only be hidden.

Real-life Example:

Think of a school principal (class) who issues a general notice. If a department head (subclass) issues a notice with the same heading, it doesn’t replace the principal’s notice; it’s just a notice from that specific department. Similarly, static methods are tied to class, not individual objects.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Cases of Method Hiding

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Case 1: Calling Superclass Static Method

A public static method in a superclass is automatically available to its subclass.
The subclass can call this method directly.

class Super {
    public static void m1() {
        System.out.println("m1 static method of super class");
    }
}

class Sub extends Super {
}

public class MethodHidingDemo1 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Sub sub = new Sub();
        sub.m1();
        System.out.println("...........");
        Sub.m1();
    }
}

Explanation:

The subclass Sub can access Super class static method m1() because static methods are inherited by default.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Case 2: Cannot Override Static with Non-Static

Static method belongs to class.
Non-static method belongs to object.
Trying to override a static method with a non-static method causes compile-time error.

class Super {
    public static void m1() {
        System.out.println("m1 static method of super class");
    }
}

class Sub extends Super {
    public void m1() { // Error: cannot override static method
        System.out.println("m1 non-static method of sub class");
    }
}

Real-life Example:

A company policy (static method) applies to all employees. An individual employee cannot make a personal rule (non-static method) that overrides the company policy.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Case 3: Cannot Override Non-Static with Static

You cannot make a static method in subclass if the superclass method is non-static.
Causes compile-time error.

class Super {
    public void m1() {
        System.out.println("m1 non-static method of super class");
    }
}

class Sub extends Super {
    public static void m1() { // Error: cannot override
        System.out.println("m1 static method of sub class");
    }
}

Conclusion:

Static ↔ Non-static overriding is not allowed.
Static methods belong to class.
Non-static methods belong to object.

Tip: Always remember: Object methods can’t override Class methods and vice versa.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Case 4: Method Hiding Only with Static Methods

Only static methods in superclass and subclass can hide each other.

class Super {
    public static void m1() {
        System.out.println("m1 static method of super class");
    }
}

class Sub extends Super {
    public static int m1() { // Method Hiding
        System.out.println("m1 static method of sub class");
        return 0;
    }
}

Key Points:

Method Hiding: static methods
Method Overriding: non-static methods

Real-life Example:

A company has a global notification system (static method in Super).

A department can send its own department-specific notification (static method in Sub) – this is method hiding, not overriding.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Case 5: Static Method Hiding Behavior

Static methods cannot be overridden.

Writing a static method in the subclass with the same signature is method hiding, not overriding.

Compiler searches for superclass method; JVM executes method according to reference type.

class Bird {
    protected static double height = 2.2;
    public static void fly() {
        System.out.println("Generic Bird is flying");
    }
}

class Parrot extends Bird {
    protected static double height = 1.2;
    public static void fly() { // Method Hiding
        System.out.println("Parrot Bird is flying");
    }
}

class Sparrow extends Bird {
    protected static double height = 1.0;
    public static void fly() { // Method Hiding
        System.out.println("Sparrow Bird is flying");
    }
}

public class MethodHidingExample1 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Bird bird = new Sparrow();
        System.out.println("Height is: " + bird.height);
        bird.fly();
    }
}

Notes:

@Override cannot be used for static methods.
Static methods behave the same for all objects → called Static Polymorphism.
A static or non-static field and static methods always execute according to current reference type.

