2. Abstraction in Java

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Definition:

Abstraction: Hiding complexity and showing only essential details.
Helps in simplifying the design and focusing on what a class does rather than how it does it.

Real-life Example:

Driving a car: you know how to drive (essential detail) without needing to understand the internal engine working (complexity).

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Achieved using:

Abstract class and abstract method → partial abstraction (0–100%)
Interface → full abstraction (100%)

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Abstract Method vs Concrete Method

| Method Type     | Example                           | Description                                     |
| --------------- | --------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| Concrete Method | `public void accept() { }`        | Instance / general method                       |
| Concrete Static | `public static void accept() { }` | Static method                                   |
| Abstract Method | `public abstract void accept();`  | No body, ends with `;`, uses `abstract` keyword |

Key Points:

Abstract methods do not have a body.
Concrete methods have implementation.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Abstract Method Scenario

abstract class Vehicle {
    public abstract void run();
}

class Bus extends Vehicle {
    public void run() { }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    public void run() { }
}

class Bike extends Vehicle {
    public void run() { }
}

Explanation:

Vehicle is abstract because the action run() is common but the implementation differs for each vehicle.

Real-life Example:

Think of Vehicle as a blueprint.
Bus, Car, Bike implement the blueprint differently: all can move (run()), but the way they move is different.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Key Points:

Use abstract method when action is common, but implementation differs.
If a class has at least one abstract method, it becomes an abstract class.
Cannot create objects of an abstract class.
Abstract methods of a superclass must be overridden in subclasses, otherwise the subclass also becomes abstract.

Extra Tips:

Abstract classes can have constructors, static methods, and fields.
They can also have concrete methods alongside abstract methods.
Interfaces (100% abstraction) are fully abstract, and a class can implement multiple interfaces for multiple inheritances.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

✅ Summary:

Method Hiding: only for static methods, reference type decides behavior.
Abstraction: hides complexity, uses abstract classes or interfaces, object-specific implementation is done in subclasses.
Real-life examples help you remember the concept quickly.

